 pages is memory pressure. "sync()",<br />&gt;     "fsync()" and "fdatasync()" will happily ignore dirty pages<br />&gt;     completely. The thing that made me overlook that simple thing in<br />&gt;     testing was that I was testing the new VM stuff under heavy VM<br />&gt;     load - to shake out any bugs.<br />&gt; <br />&gt; Does this mean anyone using test13-pre4 should also expect to see<br />&gt; data not being flushed on shutdown? <br /><br />No.<br /><br />This all only matters to things that do shared writable mmap's.<br /><br />Almost nothing does that. innd is (sadly) the only regular thing that uses<br />this, which is why it's always innd that breaks, even if everything else<br />works.<br /><br />And even innd is often compiled to use "write()" instead of shared<br />mappings (it's a config option), so not even all innd's will break.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.kernel.org<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
